question:
Find $a+b+c$, given that $x+y\neq -1$ and  \begin{align*}
ax+by+c&=x+7,\\
a+bx+cy&=2x+6y,\\
ay+b+cx&=4x+y.
\end{align*}

solution:
Since these equations look symmetric, at least on the left-hand side, we add all three together.  This gives us  \begin{align*}
&a(x+1+y)+b(y+x+1)+c(1+y+x)\\
&\qquad\qquad=x+7+2x+6y+4x+y.
\end{align*} We then factor out $(1+x+y)$ on the left and simplify the right side to get \begin{align*}
(1+x+y)(a+b+c)&=7x+7y+7, \text{ so}\\
(1+x+y)(a+b+c)&=7(1+x+y).
\end{align*}

Since $x+y\neq -1$, we know $x+y+1\neq 0$, so we can divide both sides by that term and find that $a+b+c=\boxed{7}$.

Since $39 = 2 \times 18 + 3$, the $39$th digit past the decimal point is the same as the $3$rd digit past the decimal point. To find this, we can directly divide: $$
\begin{array}{c|cccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & .0 & 5 & 2 \\
\cline{2-5}
19 & 1 & .0 & 0 & 0 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 9 & 5 & \downarrow \\ \cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 5 & 0 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 3 & 8 \\ \cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 1 & 2 \\
\end{array} $$ Thus, the answer is $\boxed{2}$.

